{
  "explanation": "The defendant committed a serious breach of fiduciary duty and trust by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. White-collar crimes of this nature require a sentence that provides general deterrence to others in similar positions of financial trust. However, the court must balance the severity of the offense with significant mitigating factors present in this case. The defendant has no prior criminal history, classifying them as a first-time offender and substantially lowering their risk of recidivism. Crucially, the defendant has already begun making restitution, demonstrating acceptance of responsibility and remorse. Ordering a prolonged period of incarceration would be counterproductive, as it would severely hinder the defendant's ability to maintain employment and pay back the remainder of the stolen funds to the victim. Therefore, a brief period of actual incarceration is appropriate to penalize the breach of trust, to be followed by a comprehensive probationary period focused on ensuring full financial restitution.",
  "verdict": 3
}
